Introducing: Juice WRLD

Who is Juice WRLD?

Juice WRLD was an American rapper, singer, and songwriter from Chicago. He gained fame for his distinctive fusion of emo and rap, with his introspective lyrics, covering themes such as heartbreak and mental health, and a melodic style. His most known hits are âLucid Dreamsâ and âRobbery.â He also received a lot of recognition for his impressive freestyle skills, as he freestyled all of his songs and has featured in shows where he rapped over multiple beats for more than an hour. Tragically, he passed away on December 8, 2019, at the age of 21, leaving behind a lasting impact on the music industry. In his short career of only two years (mainstream) he collaborated with artists such as Future, Travis Scott, Young Thug, and Eminem, making him one of the most prominent rappers of his generation.

Data Preparation

I want to remove the two albums âGoodbye & Good Riddance (5 Year Anniversary Edition)â and âGoodbye & Good Riddance (Anniversary),â because these are anniversary editions of his first album that came out in 2018 âGoodbye & Good Riddance.â If I keep all three albums, some songs will be repeated three times. Also, if I had deleted songs with the same name with the âdistinctâ code, I would end up with the latest anniversary edition that came out five years after its original release. I want to keep the original release because it is his first studio album. Moreover, one of my favorite songs is on the original release, which I want to keep on the original album.

# Remove the two 'anniversary edition' albums in order to remove duplicates
albums_to_remove <- c(
  "Goodbye & Good Riddance (5 Year Anniversary Edition)",
  "Goodbye & Good Riddance (Anniversary)"
)
Juice_WRLD <- Juice_WRLD |> filter(!(album_name %in% albums_to_remove))

Album Analysis (Valence)

In this section I will analyze the valence of each album and compare the five albums, using a boxplot for visualization. Valence is a measurement from 0 to 1.0 that describes the positiveness conveyed in a song. The most prominent changes I will make to the boxplot is abbreviating the album names on the x-axis to minimize space, and changing the colors of the albums in the plot to the colors that match the best with the color palette of the album.

# Change album_name from character to factor, and order the albums on the x-axis manually (I ordered the names by release year)
Juice_WRLD$album_name <- factor(Juice_WRLD$album_name, levels = c("Goodbye & Good Riddance", "Future & Juice WRLD Present... WRLD ON DRUGS", "Death Race For Love (Bonus Track Version)", "Legends Never Die", "Fighting Demons (Deluxe)"))

# Create a custom name for album names because otherwise the boxplot labels are unreadable
custom_album_names <- c("GB&GR", "WOD", "DFRL", "LND", "FD")

# Change colors for each album to match it with the album cover colors
custom_colors <- c("steelblue1", "mediumpurple1", "darkred", "hotpink1", "grey40")

# Plot a boxplot
ggplot(Juice_WRLD, aes(x=album_name, y=valence, color=album_name))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  labs(x="Album name", y="Valence") +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = custom_album_names)+
  scale_color_manual(values = setNames(custom_colors, levels(Juice_WRLD$album_name)), name = "Albums by Juice WRLD")

When analyzing the valence among each Juice WRLD album, we can see that âGoodbye & Good Riddanceâ has the lowest medium and is the âsaddestâ album. However, this album also has a lot of outliers, of which one is his most âpositiveâ song, which I will reveal later.

We can also see here that his latest two albums have the most range in valence. Both albums have a large range of sad and positive songs.

WRLD ON DRUGS has the highest medium, so we can say it is Juiceâs most positive album from his discography.

Overall, his albums are rather sad since most mediums are below 0.5.

Album Analysis (Danceability)

In this section I will do the exact same as the last one. However, I will replace the âvalenceâ variable with the âdanceabilityâ variable. I want to measure the danceability of each album and compare the albums to each other. Danceability is a measurement from 0 to 1.0 describing how danceable a song is.

# Change album_name from character to factor, and order the albums on the x-axis manually (I ordered the names by release year)
Juice_WRLD$album_name <- factor(Juice_WRLD$album_name, levels = c("Goodbye & Good Riddance", "Future & Juice WRLD Present... WRLD ON DRUGS", "Death Race For Love (Bonus Track Version)", "Legends Never Die", "Fighting Demons (Deluxe)"))

# Create a custom name for album names because otherwise the boxplot labels are unreadable

For danceability, WRLD ON DRUGS has (again) the highest medium and is therefore the most danceable album.

Goodbye and Good Riddance is the saddest album, but it is still rather danceable.

Overall, even though Juice WRLD makes very sad albums, they are quite danceable. Does that mean that Juice made sad albums for people to dance on?
